"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438091","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>Applicants can already register and sign in online for Rural Payments with <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438091/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T16:38:45.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438091/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438091/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-14","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he expects applicants for payments under CAP to be able to register their identity using GOV.UK Verify as planned under the new CAP regime.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438092","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-17","<p>One current HM Treasury employee has attended courses which are part of the CESG Certified Training (CCT) scheme, while three have attended other external training courses devoted entirely to Cyber Security. All HM Treasury’s employees periodically undertake online information assurance training which contains some cyber security related content, and are also provided with cyber security related guidance/advice on the Department’s intranet. All new employees have to attend induction training which contains some basic pointers on Cyber Security.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438092/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T16:07:04.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438092/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438092/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-14","Treasury: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of employees in his Department have (a) taken the CESG Certified Cyber-Security Training Course and (b) received other cyber-security training.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438093","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>The First-tier Tribunal – Social Security and Child Support (SSCS), administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS), hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ (DWP) decisions on a range of benefits including Personal Independence Payment (PIP).</p><p>Information on overall volumes of PIP appeals received is published by the Ministry of Justice in Tribunal Statistics Quarterly. The most recent report, for the period July to September 2015, can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a></p><p>Between April 2013 (when PIP was introduced) and September 2015 (the latest period for which statistics are available, 3713 PIP reassessment appeals were upheld.</p><p>HMCTS does not hold accurate information on the overall volumes of PIP reassessment appeals received.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438093/answer",,,,,"20026","2015-12-22T17:39:39.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438093/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438093/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many personal independence payment (PIP) reassessment appeals have been upheld since the introduction of PIP.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","20027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438094","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-17","<p>Personal Independence Payment is designed to ensure decisions on entitlement, award lengths and timing of reviews are appropriate and evidence-based.</p><p>All ongoing awards, regardless of duration, will be reviewed periodically to ensure that the individual continues to receive the correct amount of benefit. Where we have sufficient evidence to do so, we will conduct a paper based assessment without the need for the claimant to attend a face to face assessment.</p><p>The claimant can also ask for a review if the daily living needs or mobility needs arising change.</p><p>Reviews can result in a higher or lower award or no change.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438094/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T14:04:51.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438094/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438094/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons recipients of personal independence payments are called for reassessment.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","20024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438095","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-17","<p>Information on the number of individuals on Disability Living Allowance that have been reassessed for Personal Independence Payment is available using Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore is available here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438095/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T14:09:44.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438095/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438095/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many reassessments have been carried out for personal independent payments since the introduction of that payment.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","20025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438096","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>The First-tier Tribunal – Social Security and Child Support (SSCS), administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS), hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ (DWP) decisions on a range of benefits including Personal Independence Payment (PIP).</p><p>Information on overall volumes of PIP appeals received is published by the Ministry of Justice in Tribunal Statistics Quarterly. The most recent report, for the period July to September 2015, can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a></p><p>Between April 2013 (when PIP was introduced) and September 2015 (the latest period for which statistics are available, 3713 PIP reassessment appeals were upheld.</p><p>HMCTS does not hold accurate information on the overall volumes of PIP reassessment appeals received.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438096/answer",,,,,"20027","2015-12-22T17:39:39.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438096/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438096/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many reassessments of personal independent payments (PIP) have been appealed since the introduction of PIP.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","20026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438097","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>Over the past two financial years, the British Embassy in The Gambia has provided funding support to civil society organisations totalling £81,965. This funding has focused on ten projects relating to human rights, good governance, education, health and disease prevention and environmental conservation. The funding is part of the Embassy’s Bilateral Programme Fund and comes under Overseas Development Assistance. There is no British Council in The Gambia.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438097/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T13:15:46.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438097/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438097/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Gambia: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what funding support the British (a) Council and (b) Embassy in The Gambia provides to civil society organisations in that country.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","20007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>The UK remains concerned about The Gambia’s human rights record. We are the only EU Member State with a resident Ambassador and have a leading role in pressing the Gambian government for improved respect for human rights. We welcome some recent positive steps taken by President Jammeh, such as banning Female Genital Mutilation and the unconditional release of over 300 prisoners – including 60 high profile political prisoners. However, more needs to be done. Through our bilateral dialogue, and alongside EU partners, we will continue to make clear to the Government of The Gambia the need for further progress on its human rights record.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438098/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T13:18:51.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438098/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Gambia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in The Gambia.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","20008"
