"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437023","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-22","<p>The Government remains committed to fishing sustainably and supporting the UK’s inshore fleet. Defra is in the final stages of concluding a quota realignment exercise which, when complete, will represent a 14% uplift in the amount of quota the inshore fleet currently receives. Quota units which were under-utilised by Producer Organisations (POs) in 2012 were identified for re-allocation. Three quarters of the Fisheries Quota Allocations relating to underutilised quota from POs has now been permanently realigned to the inshore fleet, with the balance to be completed as soon as possible.</p><p>The Government has also taken steps to support England’s inshore fleet under the landing obligation, or discard ban. The demersal landing obligation comes into force on 1 January 2016, following the successful introduction of a discard ban for pelagic fisheries in 2015. The introduction of the demersal landing obligation will be phased in for all quota fisheries between 2016 and 2019. The discard plans for 2016 introduce landing obligations for clearly defined fisheries, including haddock, whiting, sole, <em>Nephrops</em>, hake and plaice.</p><p>As a result of vessels no longer being able to discard, an uplift in quota will be awarded to fishermen so they can land formerly discarded fish. The allocation of quota uplift is a devolved matter, and Minister Eustice announced the Government’s policy for allocating quota uplift for the English fleet in October this year.</p><p>In 2016, the non-sector pools will receive the first 100 tonnes of any quota uplift received and then 10% of any remainder, before the rest is issued to the POs on behalf of their members. Defra consulted on the implementation of the demersal landing obligation and responses indicate that the inshore fleets have high discard rates as a result of low quotas. The Government considers this quota uplift to go some way to helping small-scale fishermen adapt to the first year of the demersal discard ban.</p><p>As the landing obligation represents the largest change in fisheries management for a generation, it is important that we continue to support all our vessels as they adapt to this significant change. We must therefore take stock of all that is going on in fisheries management before any further decisions are made with regard to quota reallocation in the future.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437023/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-22T16:57:51.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437023/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437023/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Fisheries: Quotas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to review the UK's fishing quota, in particular with regard to whether small-scale fishermen receive a fair share of that quota.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL4489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437024","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>The South East Flexible Ticketing (SEFT) programme is proceeding with contractual obligations for five train operators who run commuter services into London. Together, these five train operators cover 73% of the annual season ticket market. We are discussing with the Rail Delivery Group and the remaining train operators the best and quickest way to deliver smart and more flexible ticketing for commuters in the south east.</p><br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437024/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T12:40:48.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437024/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437024/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-10","Railways: Season Tickets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they still plan to progress the South East Flexible Ticketing programme; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437025","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>To date, £37.64m has been spent on the South East Flexible Ticketing programme. This has facilitated investment by five train operators accounting for 73% of the annual season ticket market in the south east. Commuters on c2c and GTR can already use smartcards on their journeys into London and within the Transport for London boundary. Abellio Greater Anglia and South West Trains will follow early in 2016 and Southeastern later in the year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437025/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T12:44:45.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437025/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437025/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-10","Railways: Season Tickets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent to date on planning and developing the South East Flexible Ticketing programme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437026","Home Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The table below provides the latest published information for people detained in the detention estate by centre as at 30 September 2015, the latest date for which published figures are available.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>People in detention as at 30 September 2015, by place of detention.</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,531</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brook House IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>414</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Campsfield House IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>277</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Colnbrook IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>342</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dover IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>249</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dungavel IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>202</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Harmondsworth IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>601</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Morton Hall IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>386</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Verne IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>509</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tinsley House IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>112</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yarl's Wood IRC</p></td><td><p><strong>386</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Colnbrook STHF</p></td><td><p><strong>21</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Larne House STHF</p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pennine House STHF</p></td><td><p><strong>26</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cedars PDA</p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>IRC = Immigration Removal Centre, STHF = Short Term Holding Facility, PDA = Pre Departure Accommodation.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of people detained in the United Kingdom for immigration purposes, within the Immigration Statistics release. Data relating to people in detention are available in tables dt_01 to dt_13_q in Immigration Statistics: July – September 2015 on the GOV.UK website: https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release.</p><p>Published figures on people detained in the United Kingdom solely under Immigration Act powers include those held in short term holding facilities, pre departure accommodation and immigration removal centres. Figures exclude those held in police cells, Prison Service establishments, short term holding rooms at ports and airports (for less than 24 hours), and those recorded as detained under both criminal and immigration powers and their dependants.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437026/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T12:53:16.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437026/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437026/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people are detained in each Immigration Detention Centre.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437027","Home Office","false","2015-12-24","<p>The data on removals and voluntary departures by type and destination are available in the latest Home Office release, Immigration Statistics: July to September 2015, in table rv.06. This publication is available from GOV.UK on the statistics web pages at: https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release.</p><p>Deportations are a specific subset of removals which are enforced either following a criminal conviction or when it is judged that a person’s removal from the UK is conducive to the public good. The deportation order prohibits the person returning to the UK until such time as it may be revoked. It is not possible to separately identify deportations from enforced removals. It is not possible within these figures to say at what stage in the asylum process individuals have reached at the time of their removal, including whether their claim has failed at that point.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of persons removed or departed voluntarily from the UK and on persons refused entry to the United Kingdom within Immigration Statistics.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437027/answer","Immigration Statistics - removals and voluntary departures tables.xlsx","Immigration Statistics - removals and voluntary departures tables.xlsx","Removals and voluntary departures","Removals and voluntary departures",,"2015-12-24T11:39:47.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437027/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437027/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Asylum: Deportation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to which countries unsuccessful asylum seekers were deported in each year between 2010 and 2014, and in each of those years, how many unsuccessful asylum seekers were deported to each of those countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437028","Home Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The records the Home Office holds relate to unaccompanied asylum seeking children. The most recent records the Home Office holds are to the end of September 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>Number of Cases</p></td><td><p>Enforced Removal</p></td><td><p>Voluntary Removal</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oct 2014 - Sep 2015</p></td><td><p>241</p></td><td><p>122</p></td><td><p>119</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>This data relates to individuals who were under 18 at the time of application and aged 18 or over on the day of removal.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437028/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T12:28:19.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437028/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437028/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Deportation: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people who entered the UK as unaccompanied immigrant children were deported last year having reached the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437029","Home Office","false","2016-01-06","<p>Those who depart the UK with the additional support of an assisted package may qualify for a combination of cash and in-kind support, depending on their individual circumstances and those in the country of return. Asylum seekers may qualify for assistance equivalent to a maximum value of £1,500, and families up to £2,000 per family members.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437029/answer",,,,,,"2016-01-06T16:05:49.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437029/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437029/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Deportation: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what arrangements for care in their home countries are made for those deported on reaching the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437030","Home Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>Unaccompanied asylum seeking children are placed into the care of local authorities and are provided with specialised legal advice and support. If they have an outstanding asylum claim on reaching the age of 18, legal advice will continue to be provided and their social worker will help them to access that support.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437030/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T12:54:08.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437030/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437030/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what provision is made to enable young asylum seekers to have legal support and advice on reaching the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437031","Home Office","false","2015-12-24","<p>The number of cases where individuals facing deportation have committed self harm or suicide cannot be extracted without incurring disproportionate cost. Figures therefore cannot be provided.</p><p>The Home Office is committed to ensuring adequate safeguards are in place for those where there are concerns about self harm or suicide. Guidance has been provided to immigration case workers, and there is a requirement to share concerns with other officers involved in the case by noting such concerns on the Department’s case information database (CID).</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437031/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-24T11:38:57.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437031/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437031/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Asylum: Deportation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how many asylum seekers facing deportation committed self harm or suicide in the past year.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437032","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>An invitation to the briefing on the Northern Ireland (Welfare Reform) Bill held on Monday 23 November was circulated electronically to all Peers via the Usual Channels.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437032/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-23T09:53:02.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437032/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437032/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-12-10","Welfare State: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which peers and MPs were invited to attend a briefing with the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland on the Northern Ireland (Welfare Reform) Bill on 23 November.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL4498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437033","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The Peers who attended the briefing with the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland on the Northern Ireland (Welfare Reform) Bill included: Lord McAvoy; Baroness Randerson; and Lord Trimble.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437033/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-23T09:52:35.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437033/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437033/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-12-10","Welfare State: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which peers and MPs attended the briefing with the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland on the Northern Ireland (Welfare Reform) Bill on 23 November.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL4499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437034","Department of Health","false","2015-12-21","<p>To model the increased demographic demand on state funded adult social care the Department commissioned modelling from the Personal Social Services Research Unit (PSSRU). PSSRU’s analysis is currently in the process of being peer reviewed prior to publication.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437034/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T17:14:46.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437034/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437034/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 10 December (HL3975), what was the increase in demand they assumed and modelled for social care year on year for each year between 2015 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437035","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>I can confirm that every country in the Middle East has received a visit from a member of the Royal Family.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437035/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T14:43:19.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437035/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437035/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Middle East: Royal Visits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which countries in the Middle East have never received a formal visit from a member of the Royal Family.","false","Biography information for Lord Sherbourne of Didsbury",,"Lord Sherbourne of Didsbury","HL4501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437036","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>The purpose of the tax-advantaged venture capital schemes is to encourage investment into smaller, higher risk companies that would otherwise struggle to access the funding they need to develop and grow.</p><br /><p>Changes have been made to the schemes over time to ensure that asset-backed activities, as well as those that benefit from predictable and reliable income streams, do not qualify, since these often represent lower-risk investments that should be able to secure finance without the need for tax relief. For example, different types of energy generation were excluded from the schemes in 2012, 2014 and 2015, due to clear evidence that such investments were particularly low-risk products offering return of capital, and were being explicitly marketed as such.</p><br /><p>Community energy projects in receipt of other government support were not excluded at the time of these previous changes. However, since then the government has become aware of significantly increased interest in the use of community energy for low-risk tax planning purposes. The number of community energy schemes registered as community interest companies (CICs) or community benefit societies has increased from about 5 in 2014 to about 200 by October 2015. The marketing material of these investments suggests that the level of investment risk for community energy, including solar, is comparable to that of activities that were previously excluded.</p><br /><p>The government announced at the Summer Budget 2015 that it would monitor the use of the venture capital schemes by community energy organisations to ensure that there was continued value for money for the taxpayer and that they were not the subject of misuse. The government subsequently announced the exclusion of subsidised renewable energy generation by community energy organisations on 26 October 2015, taking effect for investments made on or after 30 November 2015, providing a notice period of five weeks. At the same time, the government announced the exclusion of activities making reserve energy generating capacity available, also with effect for investments made on or after 30 November 2015.</p><br /><p>The government believes that the notice period given provided a good balance between the provision of notice to potential investors who might wish to take advantage of the tax reliefs provided through the schemes and the financial risk to the Exchequer that a longer notice period would carry.</p><br /><p>To further ensure the venture capital schemes remain well-targeted and deliver value for money, the government announced at Autumn Statement 2015 the exclusion of all remaining energy generation activities from the schemes with effect for investments made on or after 6 April 2016. The new exclusions will apply to both non-renewable and renewable sources of energy generation and apply irrespective of whether a subsidy is received or of the nature of the company carrying on the activities.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437036/answer",,,,,"HL4503","2015-12-23T10:26:02.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437036/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437036/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-10","Energy: Enterprise Investment Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they afforded community energy schemes less than one month’s notice for the implementation of changes to the tax rules, but allowed a phasing out of Enterprise Investment Scheme relief for all generation projects over a longer period.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL4502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437037","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>The purpose of the tax-advantaged venture capital schemes is to encourage investment into smaller, higher risk companies that would otherwise struggle to access the funding they need to develop and grow.</p><br /><p>Changes have been made to the schemes over time to ensure that asset-backed activities, as well as those that benefit from predictable and reliable income streams, do not qualify, since these often represent lower-risk investments that should be able to secure finance without the need for tax relief. For example, different types of energy generation were excluded from the schemes in 2012, 2014 and 2015, due to clear evidence that such investments were particularly low-risk products offering return of capital, and were being explicitly marketed as such.</p><br /><p>Community energy projects in receipt of other government support were not excluded at the time of these previous changes. However, since then the government has become aware of significantly increased interest in the use of community energy for low-risk tax planning purposes. The number of community energy schemes registered as community interest companies (CICs) or community benefit societies has increased from about 5 in 2014 to about 200 by October 2015. The marketing material of these investments suggests that the level of investment risk for community energy, including solar, is comparable to that of activities that were previously excluded.</p><br /><p>The government announced at the Summer Budget 2015 that it would monitor the use of the venture capital schemes by community energy organisations to ensure that there was continued value for money for the taxpayer and that they were not the subject of misuse. The government subsequently announced the exclusion of subsidised renewable energy generation by community energy organisations on 26 October 2015, taking effect for investments made on or after 30 November 2015, providing a notice period of five weeks. At the same time, the government announced the exclusion of activities making reserve energy generating capacity available, also with effect for investments made on or after 30 November 2015.</p><br /><p>The government believes that the notice period given provided a good balance between the provision of notice to potential investors who might wish to take advantage of the tax reliefs provided through the schemes and the financial risk to the Exchequer that a longer notice period would carry.</p><br /><p>To further ensure the venture capital schemes remain well-targeted and deliver value for money, the government announced at Autumn Statement 2015 the exclusion of all remaining energy generation activities from the schemes with effect for investments made on or after 6 April 2016. The new exclusions will apply to both non-renewable and renewable sources of energy generation and apply irrespective of whether a subsidy is received or of the nature of the company carrying on the activities.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437037/answer",,,,,"HL4502","2015-12-23T10:26:02.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437037/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437037/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-10","Energy: Enterprise Investment Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have of misuse of the Enterprise Investment Scheme for community energy projects that contributed to their decision to withdraw the scheme for those purposes.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL4503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437038","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2015-12-21","<p><strong>The full public consultation on the ‘Moving around’ activity of the mobility component closed on 5 August 2013. We received more than 1,100 responses. We carefully considered all the responses received, including the suggestions for alternative approaches. We published our response to the consultation on 21 October 2013.</strong></p><br /><p><strong>We believe the assessment criteria, including the 20 metres distance, are the best way of identifying those whose physical mobility is most limited, so we did not make any changes. However, we have strengthened the measures around the reliability criteria – we recognise these are a key protection for claimants.</strong></p><br /><p><strong>Our response to the consultation is annexed to this answer.</strong></p>",,"Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437038/answer","Annex HL 4504.pdf","Annex HL 4504.pdf","Annex "Moving around activity"","Annex "Moving around activity"",,"2015-12-21T12:19:10.83Z","2015-12-22T14:16:11.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437038/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437038/answer",,"Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437038/answer/previousversion/36662","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Altmann on 4 December (HL3783) that the Personal Independence Payment assessment criteria were "designed in close collaboration with disabled people and disability groups", whether they will now take into account the responses to the consultation held separately between 24 June and 5 August 2013 on the moving around criteria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL4504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437039","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The guidance for health professionals undertaking assessments for Personal Independence Payment specifies that for a descriptor to be able to apply to a claimant, the claimant must be able to complete the activity reliably i.e. safely, to an acceptable standard, repeatedly and in a reasonable time period. For a report to be considered fully acceptable it must include confirmation that the health professional has fully considered these reliability criteria.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437039/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-22T16:02:26.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437039/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437039/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have introduced a requirement for health professionals involved in the Personal Independence Payment assessment to confirm that they have referred to the reliability criteria when formulating their advice.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL4505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437040","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The PIP Assessment Guide for Health Professionals carrying out assessments includes guidance on the assessment criteria and how they should be applied. The guide is regularly reviewed to ensure that the criteria is applied consistently and fairly.</p><br /><p>Chapter 3 – ‘The Assessment Criteria’ (page 73) explains how to apply the reliability criteria, including in the ‘Moving Around’ activity. We have also provided a worked example to further assist health professionals.</p><br /><p>The latest version of the guide is annexed to this answer.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437040/answer","Annex HL 4506.pdf","Annex HL 4506.pdf","Annex "PIP Assessment Guide"","Annex "PIP Assessment Guide"",,"2015-12-22T14:16:56.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437040/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437040/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have revisited the Personal Independence Payment assessment moving around guidance on reliability to ensure that that guidance captures real-life situations and that the criteria are applied consistently and fairly.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL4506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437041","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Natural Environment Research Council is currently funding two research programmes to detect changes in the Gulf Stream and to investigate how these changes might affect the weather of the North Atlantic (RAPID-AMOC and ODYSEA). DECC co-funds, with Defra, the Met Office Hadley Centre Climate Programme which, amongst many other research activities, uses climate models to understand the observed fluctuations in the Gulf Stream, to predict future changes, and to assess the impact that present and future changes may have upon European weather and climate.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437041/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T14:03:46.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437041/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437041/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what studies they are undertaking into the slowing of the Gulf Stream and the subsequent impact on climate change and extreme weather patterns in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL4507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437042","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The Jubilee Medals come ahead of the Ebola Medal for Service in West Africa in the current Order of Wear.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437042/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-23T10:52:19.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437042/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437042/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-10","Medals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the new Ebola medal takes precedence over jubilee medals in the order of wear.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437043","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<br /><p>I can confirm that officials are currently working on the eligibility criteria for a new Long Service Medal. Details will be made available in 2016.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437043/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T16:34:03.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437043/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437043/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Military Decorations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any decision has been made about the introduction of the new Long Service medal proposed by the Secretary of State for Defence in March.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437044","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>The decision on whether to operate embarked or disembarked squadrons will be taken by the Strategic Headquarters in the Ministry of Defence.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437044/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T12:37:04.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437044/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437044/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Aircraft Carriers: Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who will decide when Sea Lightning squadrons are embarked or disembarked on the Queen Elizabeth class aircraft carriers.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437045","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>Command of embarked aircraft will be dependent on a variety of factors such as but not limited to, the specific task, whether it is a national or coalition commitment, threat levels and theatre of operations.</p><br />",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437045/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T12:35:43.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437045/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437045/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Aircraft Carriers: Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the embarked carrier air wing of Sea Lightnings, Merlins, Crowsnest aircraft, and Wildcats will be under Maritime Task Force command.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437046","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<br /><br /><p>When necessary to deliver the carrier strike programme, embarked jointly manned F-35B air squadrons will operate to the same harmony guidelines.</p><br /><p>Deck qualifications will not be affected by harmony rules.</p><br /><p><br></p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437046/answer",,,,,"HL4513","2015-12-16T16:36:04.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437046/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437046/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Aircraft Carriers: Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether embarked carrier air squadrons will follow the "all of one company" rule and operate under the same harmony rules.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437047","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<br /><br /><p>When necessary to deliver the carrier strike programme, embarked jointly manned F-35B air squadrons will operate to the same harmony guidelines.</p><br /><p>Deck qualifications will not be affected by harmony rules.</p><br /><p><br></p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437047/answer",,,,,"HL4512","2015-12-16T16:36:04.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437047/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437047/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Aircraft Carriers: Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of different elements of embarked carrier squadrons working to different harmony rules and whether it will affect deck qualifications such as that for night flying.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4513"
