"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437053","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<br /><p>The Healthy Identity Intervention (HII) has not been accredited by the Correctional Services Advice &amp; Accreditation panel (CSAAP) as it is not compatible with the criteria currently used.</p><p>There have been 65 HII completions since its pilot in 2010-11. Sixteen people are currently undertaking HII. There are currently 15 people waiting to begin the intervention. This can be for a number of reasons, including involvement in other offender behaviour programmes, or mental health problems.</p><p>Healthy Identity is targeted at those convicted under the terrorism legislation where extremism was their primary motive. Where violence is the primary motive, other Offender Behaviour programmes may be used. Healthy Identity Interventions is not commissioned for specific establishments in the same way as other offending behaviour programmes. HII is available widely across England and Wales prisons and probation services. It is delivered by trained chartered psychologists and experienced probation officers. There are currently 145 trained HII facilitators.</p><br /> <br />",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437053/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-22T17:09:04.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437053/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437053/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-10","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people have undergone the programme of deradicalisation referred to as the Healthy Identities Intervention since it was accredited; how many people are awaiting access to the programme; which establishments currently offer the programme; and how many programmes are being offered at each establishment, including the number of individuals able to access each course.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws",,"Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws","HL4519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437054","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>It is fair that families on benefits have to make the same financial decisions as families supporting themselves solely through work. These measures are being actively discussed in the Committee stage of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill (as the Minister informed the House) and there will be further discussion at the Report stage.</p><br />",,"Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437054/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-22T12:25:38.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437054/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437054/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Social Security Benefits: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many kinship care households they estimate will be affected by the combined impact of the proposals in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill to limit child tax credit to two children and to reduce the benefit cap in each year between 2016 and 2021; what is their estimate of the cost of exempting kinship care households from those measures; and what impact assessment has been carried out as to how many potential kinship carers may be unable to afford to take on the children as a result of those measures and any consequential cost to the state of such children remaining in the care system.","false","Biography information for Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top",,"Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top","HL4520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437055","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-23","<p>The Department collects information for those aged 18 to 24 and the latest information available at May 2015 shows that for this age group there were 121,950 lone parents receiving Income Support and 3,500 people, without an additional payment for a partner and with at least one dependent child, receiving Jobseeker’s Allowance (JSA).</p><p>Please note that the figures are rounded to the nearest ten.</p><p>The information requested for those who are care leavers is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437055/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-23T09:51:27.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437055/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437055/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Social Security Benefits: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many single parents aged between 18 and 25 currently receive Income Support and Jobseeker’s Allowance; and of those, how many they estimate are care leavers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top",,"Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top","HL4521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437056","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>",,"Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437056/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-22T11:31:29.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437056/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437056/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-10","Universal Credit: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the cost in each year between 2016 and 2021 of young parents under 25 years old, who are single claimants and care leavers, receiving the same rate of standard allowance in universal credit as single claimants who are parents aged 25 years old; and how many people this would affect.","false","Biography information for Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top",,"Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top","HL4522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437057","Attorney General","false","2015-12-15","<p>In the last financial year the CPS successfully prosecuted 130 human trafficking cases. However, the CPS does not record how an allegation of human trafficking or modern slavery was brought to the attention of the investigative authorities.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437057/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T13:01:57.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437057/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437057/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-12-10","Human Trafficking: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many alleged human traffickers have been prosecuted by the CPS as a result of calls made to the NSPCC human trafficking and modern slavery helpline between July 2014 and June 2015.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","19543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437058","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-18","<p>Officials in the department meet with their counterparts in the Northern Ireland Executive on a regular basis, to discuss a range of matters connected to small business, including Small Business Saturday.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437058/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T14:50:24.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437058/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437058/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-10","Small Businesses: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on Small Business Saturday and its benefits to promoting the value of small businesses to the economy.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","19513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437059","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-15","<p>HM Treasury and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, conducted internal modelling on which rate and scope would result in sufficient levels of income to fund growth in high-quality apprenticeships up until 2020. It will continue to conduct analysis and have an open dialogue with employers to understand the cost and benefits of the apprenticeship levy.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437059/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:07:16.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437059/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437059/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-10","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what modelling his Department conducted on the effect of the Apprenticeship Levy prior to its announcement.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","19529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437060","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-17","<p>The National Student Survey (NSS) annually gathers students’ opinions on the quality of their course. The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) published a separate report in 2014 which provides analysis on the differences between NSS results for different student characteristics over the period 2005-2013.</p><p>A copy of the report and a tool, which allows the data to be filtered by different student characteristics including disability, are available on the HEFCE website at</p><p><a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/pubs/2014/201413/HEFCE2014_13%20-%20corrected%2012%20December%202014.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/pubs/2014/201413/HEFCE2014_13%20-%20corrected%2012%20December%202014.pdf</a></p><p><a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/nsstrend/" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/nsstrend/ </a></p><p>Higher education institutions have a legal duty under the Equality Act 2010 to provide reasonable adjustments for disabled students and to monitor their compliance with their Equality Act duties. The Equality Act 2010 (Specific Duties) Regulations 2011 require institutions to publish information as to their compliance with the general public sector equality duty.</p><p>The Independent Office for Fair Access (OFFA) has agreed 183 Access Agreements for 2016/17 with plans for universities to spend more than £745 million on measures to improve access and student success for students from disadvantaged backgrounds, up from £404m in 2009/10. Higher education institutions choose their own access agreement measures and targets, in line with their own particular mission and challenges and these can include targets on disability where appropriate.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437060/answer",,,,,"19504","2015-12-17T11:31:55.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437060/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437060/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-10","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on satisfaction levels of (a) non-disabled and (b) disabled students of their experience in higher education.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","19503"
