"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437119","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>In the 2015 Spending Round, my rt. hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer (George Osborne), announced £500 million for the Disabled Facilities Grant by 2020. Since April 2015, the Grant has been part of the Government's £5.3 billion Better Care Fund, promoting integration with health and social care.</p><p>Annual allocations for the Disabled Facilities Grant for each year until 2020 will be announced in due course, when they are finalised.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437119/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:40:26.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437119/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437119/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-10","Disabled Facilities Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the level of Government spending will be on the Disabled Facilities Grant for each year until 2020.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","19637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437120","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-18","<p>We are currently analysing responses to the discussion paper ‘Parking reform: tackling unfair practices’ issued earlier this year. The suggestion to establish a standards setting body with a code of practice and an appeals service for all accredited trade associations for the management of parking on private land was made in some responses, and we are actively considering this point as part of our wider work on parking. We will publish our response to the discussion paper in the New Year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437120/answer",,,,,"19603","2015-12-18T14:32:16.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437120/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437120/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-10","Parking: Unfair Practices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he will respond to the submissions to his Department's consultation, Parking reform: tackling unfair practices, of March 2015.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","19654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437121","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-18","<p>Responsibility for off-street parking transferred to DCLG in March of 2015, including Schedule 4 of the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012 and those aspects of the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984 and the Traffic Management Act 2004 which relate to off-street parking.</p><p>The Department of Health have responsibly for setting the policy contect by which hopsital car parks operate and the Department of Transport retain an interest in railway parking. My Department has reponsibility for Local Authority housing estates.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437121/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T14:32:56.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437121/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437121/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-10","Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department's policy remit on off-street parking includes parking for healthcare facilities, railway stations and local authority housing estates.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","19655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437122","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>We will be publishing the prospectus for the 2016-21 Affordable Homes Programme in the New Year, which will set out the assessment requirements that bids contributing towards the 8,000 vulnerable, older and disabled peoples housing will be assessed against.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437122/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:48:53.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437122/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437122/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-10","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the accessibility requirements will be for the 8,000 new accessible homes announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015; and where those homes will be located.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","19621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437123","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>Annual correspondence with the FTSE 100 companieshas indicated that from 2013 to present there has been a steady increase in the number of companies that provide video relay. With regards to public sector, DWP plan to launch a pilot service by the end of the year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437123/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T10:08:40.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437123/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437123/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-10","Telecommunications: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will commission research on the proportion of public and private service providers which offer access to their services through video relay.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","19531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437124","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>My Departmenthas been in contact with TalkTalk from the early stages of this incident, but this remains primarily a matter for the company itself and for law enforcement</p><p>This Governmenttakes issues of customer data protection very seriously, andhas regular discussions with internet service providers and telecommunications companies on the resilience and security of services. I recently wrote to FTSE 350 companies to remind them of the steps the Government expects them to take and the robust procedures businesses need to have in place. I also invited them to take part in the Government's annual Cyber Governance Health Check to help companies understand and improve their level of cyber security.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437124/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T10:13:00.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437124/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437124/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-10","Communication Service Providers: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with (a) Talk Talk and (b) other internet service providers on measures that can be taken to prevent breaches of security relating to customer data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","19629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437125","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government believes that all-seater stadiums are the best means to ensure the safety and security of fans at football in England and Wales. All-seater stadiums have helped improve crowd management, crowd behaviour and policing. They also provide more comfortable facilities to enjoy football matches.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437125/answer",,,,,"12142","2015-12-15T11:57:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437125/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437125/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-10","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to respond to Question 12142, tabled by the hon. Member for Coventry South on 15 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","19633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437126","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer of 7 December to Question 18571 where the operating costs for each centre from the past four financial years was provided. It is not possible to provide costs per training event as, due to the variation in course length, delivery is measured on the total number of training weeks delivered, which was also provided in that response.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437126/answer","Hansard Extract 7 December 2015 HOC 18571.docx","Hansard Extract 7 December 2015 HOC 18571.docx","Armed Forces Training","Armed Forces Training",,"2015-12-15T16:19:08.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437126/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437126/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 4 December 2015 to Question 18406, whether his Department assesses the cost of any training courses undertaken by (a) RAF, (b) navy and (c) army personnel at (i) Granton-on-Spey, (ii) Llanrwst, (iii) Crickhowell and (iv) Fairbourne; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","19569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437127","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>The term &quot;air warfare personnel&quot; is not recognised within the Royal Air Force. Allocation of manpower is sensibly prioritised to ensure that operational needs are met in full.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437127/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T12:03:52.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437127/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437127/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Air Force: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to reduce shortages in the number of trained air warfare personnel; and what assessment he has made of the effect of that shortage on military operations in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","19518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437128","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>To safeguard operational security I am withholding operational information on the number of RAF Reaper aircraft deployed.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437128/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T12:05:40.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437128/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437128/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-10","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Reaper drones are currently deployed in (a) Iraq and (b) Syria.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","19519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437129","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>The department does not conduct such assessments or collect data on individual schools’ admission arrangements. The department does publish data on the ethnicity of pupils enrolled at schools in England. This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a></p><br /><p>It is for individual schools with a faith designation to decide whether or not to adopt faith-based admission arrangements, in the local context of their school.</p><br /><p>When constructing faith-based oversubscription criteria, they must have due regard to the guidance of their religious authority, and their arrangements must comply with the School Admissions Code.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437129/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T18:01:47.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437129/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437129/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the relationship between faith-based admissions policies and ethnic diversity in (a) primary and (b) secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","19520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437130","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>All schools are subject to the Equality Act 2010 and must comply with the requirements of the Schools Admission Code. The legislation is already available within the Equality Act 2010 and the Admission Code, which ensures schools meet their statutory requirements ensuring that a diverse ethnic group of pupils attend both Catholic and non-Catholic schools.</p><br /><p>The department does not conduct comparative assessments of ethnicity diversity among pupils of Catholic schools and non-Catholic schools.</p><br />","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437130/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T18:00:36.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437130/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437130/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Pupils: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what comparative assessment her Department has made of the ethnic diversity among pupils of Catholic schools and non-Catholic schools.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","19521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437131","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-15","<p>Higher education institutions have a legal duty under the Equality Act 2010 to provide reasonable adjustments for disabled students and to monitor their compliance with their Equality Act duties. The Equality Act 2010 (Specific Duties) Regulations 2011 require institutions to publish information as to their compliance with the general public sector equality duty.</p><p>Students who are dissatisfied with the provision of support, and raise their concerns through their institution’s formal complaints procedures, can then also take their case to the Office of the Independent Adjudicator. This is a free service for the student.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437131/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T14:53:30.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437131/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437131/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-10","Higher Education: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the Independent Adjudicator can monitor the implementation by higher education institutions of provision for disabled students who do not have complex needs.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","19505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437132","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>The department does not conduct assessments on how effective Catholic schools are in supporting the integration of minority communities in their student body and the wider community.</p><br /><p>All state-funded schools are required to teach a broad and balanced curriculum, actively promote fundamental British values and have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations between peoples of different backgrounds and faiths. Pupils are taught about diverse national, regional, religious and ethnic identities in the UK and the need for mutual respect and understanding. Ofsted’s inspection framework includes a focus on pupils' spiritual, moral, social and cultural development. Under the Equality Act 2010 Faith schools are not allowed to treat pupils less favourably in any other way because of their religion or belief, or lack of belief. Under the Public Equality Duty, faith schools must also have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, promote equality of opportunity, and foster good relations between different groups.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437132/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T17:59:10.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437132/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437132/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Faith Schools: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of Catholic schools in supporting the integration of minority communities in (a) their student body and (b) the wider community.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","19522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437133","Department for Education","false","2015-12-17","<p>The new computing curriculum, introduced in September 2014 and compulsory for ages 5-16, has been designed to ensure the study of topics such as computational logic, algorithms and coding.</p><br /><p>The government has spent more than £4.5 million over the past three years to support schools in delivering high quality computing teaching. This includes £3 million for Computing At School to build a national network of over 350 ‘Master Teachers’ in computer science whom schools can commission to provide training for their teachers.</p><br /><p>In primary school, pupils will be looking at designing, writing and debugging programs. With these skills, pupils can create games or useful tools like a number generator for maths.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437133/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T17:17:19.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437133/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437133/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","ICT: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to promote coding as part of the curriculum or otherwise amongst young people.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","19546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437134","Department for Education","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Secretary of State holds discussions on a range of topics with Cabinet Ministers.</p><br /><p>The National Crime Agency (NCA) has recently published guidance on preventing young people from becoming involved in cyber-crime: <a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/crime-threats/cyber-crime/cyber-crime-preventing-young-people-from-getting-involved" target="_blank">www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/crime-threats/cyber-crime/cyber-crime-preventing-young-people-from-getting-involved</a></p><p><br></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437134/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T17:16:25.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437134/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437134/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Cybercrime: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the page on the National Crime Agency website entitled, Cyber crime: Preventing young people from getting involved, what discussions she has had with the Home Secretary on interest in coding and possession of independent learning material on computing being considered possible indicators of risk of involvement in cyber crime.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","19545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437135","Department for Education","false","2015-12-15","<p>There are opportunities across the school curriculum for children to be taught the skills they need to make healthy food choices. In science lessons at key stages 1 and 2, children are taught to describe the importance for humans of exercise and eating the right amounts of different types of food and that humans need the right types and amount of nutrition. In secondary science, children are taught about the content of a healthy human diet, such as carbohydrates, fats and oils, proteins, vitamins, minerals, dietary fibre and water, and why each is needed. They also learn about the consequences of imbalances in the diet, including obesity.</p><p>In design and technology lessons (key stages 1 to 3), children are taught about food, nutrition and healthy eating and how to cook a repertoire of dishes. Pupils in primary schools are taught about healthy eating and the importance of a good, balanced diet. In secondary schools, children’s knowledge becomes more in-depth as they learn how to feed themselves and others affordably and well and learn where their food comes from.</p><p>Personal, Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education also provides opportunities for pupils to learn about health and wellbeing, including being taught what constitutes a healthy lifestyle, the benefits of physical activity and healthy eating.</p><p>It is important that children eat nutritious, tasty food at school as fuel for learning, to help their growth and development and so that they develop healthy eating habits. The School Food Standards, introduced in January 2015, severely restrict foods high in fat, salt and sugar, as well as low quality reformed or reconstituted foods. They help ensure that pupils always have healthy options for their school lunch.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437135/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:17:03.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437135/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437135/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Food: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that children and young people acquire the skills necessary to make healthy food choice.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","19586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437136","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>All schools are required, by law, to have a behaviour policy with measures to prevent and tackle all forms of bullying and they are held closely to account by Ofsted for their effectiveness.</p><p>We have provided advice to schools on how to support children that are bullied. This makes clear that this might include pastoral support, counselling or peer mediation, engaging parents and in some cases offering separate on-site educational provision to provide respite for the bullied individual so they are able to continue to attend school. In extreme cases, where a child has developed complex needs as a result of bullying, which cannot be met in mainstream education, then alternative provision may need to be arranged. Our advice to schools can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/preventing-and-tackling-bullying" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/preventing-and-tackling-bullying</a></p><p>To help schools tackle bullying we are providing £1.3 million of funding over 12 months from April 2015 to various anti-bullying charities including the Diana Award, Kidscape and the National Children’s Bureau. These organisations train teachers and pupils in schools to prevent bullying and deal with its impact when it occurs so that bullied children do not suffer continuing distress. This is in addition to the £4 million provided in 2013/15.</p><p>The Longitudinal Study of Young People in England (LSYPE) published by my Department in November 2015 compared bullying among two cohorts of 14 year olds (year 10) from 2004 and 2014. This shows that, while there is clearly much more to do, thanks to the efforts of teachers and charities 30,000 fewer people in year 10 said they had been bullied in the last twelve months - a drop from 41 per cent in 2004 to 36 per cent in 2014.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437136/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T18:05:42.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437136/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437136/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-10","Pupils: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will introduce additional support for children experiencing bullying.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","19591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437137","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-16","<p>We do not break down published information on components of Levy Control Framework (LCF) spend to the level of detail requested, due to potential disclosure of commercially confidential information.</p><p>On 25 November 2015, the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) published LCF projected spend of just under £9bn in 2020/21 (see Tables 1 and 2 below)<sup>1</sup>. Between the projections Government published in November 20142 and this forecast, we have undertaken analysis to make changes to many assumptions, including technology-specific factors (including offshore wind), fossil fuel prices and electricity demand3. Collectively, changes in these factors have all affected overall estimates of LCF spend. However, we do not provide published estimates of how much is attributable to each individual factor. DECC will publish a further update to its projections, including the underpinning assumptions, in 2016.</p><p><br> <br> <br> <br></p><p><strong>Annex A</strong></p><br /><p><strong>Table 1: OBR November 2015 main projections were as follows:</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Policy (£m, nominal prices)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>RO</strong></p></td><td><p>3,850</p></td><td><p>4,615</p></td><td><p>5,375</p></td><td><p>5,855</p></td><td><p>6,035</p></td><td><p>6,230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>FiTs</strong></p></td><td><p>1,325</p></td><td><p>1,515</p></td><td><p>1,700</p></td><td><p>1,880</p></td><td><p>2,055</p></td><td><p>2,220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CfDs</strong></p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>225</p></td><td><p>545</p></td><td><p>1,095</p></td><td><p>2,225</p></td><td><p>2,805</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>5,190</p></td><td><p>6,355</p></td><td><p>7,620</p></td><td><p>8,830</p></td><td><p>10,315</p></td><td><p>11,255</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest five million pounds. Totals may not sum due to rounding.</p><br /><p><strong>Table 2: OBR November 2015 main projections in 2011/12 prices</strong>:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>£m, 2011/12 prices</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>RO</strong></p></td><td><p>3,360</p></td><td><p>3,990</p></td><td><p>4,555</p></td><td><p>4,820</p></td><td><p>4,820</p></td><td><p>4,820</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>FiTs</strong></p></td><td><p>1,155</p></td><td><p>1,310</p></td><td><p>1,440</p></td><td><p>1,550</p></td><td><p>1,640</p></td><td><p>1,720</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CfDs</strong></p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>210</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p>980</p></td><td><p>1,950</p></td><td><p>2,415</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>4,530</p></td><td><p>5,505</p></td><td><p>6,495</p></td><td><p>7,350</p></td><td><p>8,415</p></td><td><p>8,955</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest five million pounds. Totals may not sum due to rounding.</p><p><br></p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> Note that OBR publishes figures in nominal terms, as opposed to our figures which are in 2011/12 real prices. Both sets of figures are attached at Annex A</em></p><p><em>2</em><em> Annual Energy Statement, page 73, https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/371388/43586_Cm_8945_print_ready.pdf </em></p><p><em>3</em><em> Data on fossil fuel prices and electricity demand assumptions have recently been published online at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fossil-fuel-price-projections-2015 and https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/updated-energy-and-emissions-projections-2015 respectively.</em></p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437137/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T15:32:06.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437137/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437137/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much overspend against original estimates within the levy control framework has arisen from variations in (a) performance of offshore wind, (b) levels between strike price and reference price and (c) variations in allocations feed in tariff payments for solar PV installations in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437138","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>There have been no such legal challenges in the last year.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437138/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:35:31.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437138/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437138/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many legal challenges have been made against her Department related to renewable energy policy in the last year.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","19696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437139","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>We will be publishing the Government response to the review of the feed-in tariff as soon as possible detailing the changes we will make to the scheme.</p><p><br> <br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437139/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:35:01.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437139/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437139/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the feed-in tariff scheme will be paused in January 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","19697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437140","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government proposed changes to the feed-in tariff scheme (FITs) as part of the FIT review, on which we consulted widely between 27<sup>th</sup> August and 23<sup>rd</sup> October. Part of the purpose of that consultation was to gather views on the broader economic impact of the proposals. The actual impact on the sector will, of course, depend on the options taken forward after all responses to the consultation have been considered. We intend to publish a Government response as soon as possible.</p><br /><p>The ONS has published first estimates of the UK’s ‘Low Carbon and Renewable Energy Economy’1 based on 2014; further information from this survey on sub-sectors including solar PV jobs will be published in 2016.</p><br /><p>[1] <em><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171776_426448.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171776_426448.pdf</a></em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437140/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:43:24.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437140/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437140/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Solar Power: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the change in the number of jobs in the UK solar industry has been since the Summer Budget 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","19695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437141","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility published updated projections on spending under the Levy Control Framework on 25 November:</p><br /><p><a href="http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/economic-fiscal-outlook-november-2015/" target="_blank">http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/economic-fiscal-outlook-november-2015/</a>.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437141/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T15:31:15.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437141/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437141/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what level of actual or projected overspend against original projections of expenditure under the Levy Control Framework she has identified for each year from 2014 to 2018; and in which of those years overspend has exceeded the 20 per cent headroom within the Levy Control Framework agreement between her Department and HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437142","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-16","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State made two separate visits to the COP21 conference in Paris. For the first, she travelled out by train and returned by plane. For the second she travelled there and back by train.</p><br /><p>In accordance with the Ministerial Code, it was ensured that these were the most efficient and cost-effective options for the Secretary of State to meet her commitments at COP.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437142/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T15:29:05.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437142/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437142/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Climate Change Convention: Paris","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what form of transport she used to travel to the COP21 conference in Paris in December 2015; and for what reasons she used that form of transport.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437143","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State wrote to the European Commissioner for Trade in November, requesting ending the minimum import price.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437143/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:38:30.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437143/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437143/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-10","Solar Power: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she has written to the European Commissioner for Trade on ending the minimum import price on Chinese solar panels.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","19514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437144","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-16","<p>Environmental Stewardship (ES) claims are administered by Natural England. Historically, about 60% of advance payments have previously been paid in August.</p><br /><p>All ES and Basic Payment Scheme claims have to be cross-checked before payment can be made in line with European regulatory requirements. This year, due mainly to the extension of the claims deadline, it was necessary to delay ES advance payments until they could be cross-checked. From 2018, new European rules will prevent any payments from being made before 16 October each year.</p><br /><p>Natural England had paid 28,523 (60.24%) of advance payments by the end of October. Ninety-two percent of ES advance payments have now been made, and Natural England aims to pay the remainder of advance claims by the end of December.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437144/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T13:21:01.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437144/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437144/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Environmental Stewardship Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of farmers who received payments under the Environment Stewardship Scheme in October rather than August 2015 as a result of the withdrawal of online applications for such payments.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437145","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>The new Common Agricultural Policy has been widely recognised as being more complex for farmers to understand and harder for Member States to administer. The new schemes have not yet been audited by the European Commission so it is too early to say what the level of any disallowance will be, but complexity tends to increase disallowance risk.</p><br /><p>For the Basic Payment Scheme 2015 the Rural Payments Agency (RPA) sent pre-populated claim forms to farmers and land owners to allow them to submit their applications before the deadline. The RPA provided an unprecedented level of support to farmers and land owners through the Rural Payments Helpline and 50 Drop In Centres that allowed some 88,000 applications to be received within the deadline. ‘Paper-assisted’ means that forms were completed on paper but then entered on to a digital system by RPA staff.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437145/answer",,,,,"19643","2015-12-15T12:46:06.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437145/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437145/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the cost of disallowance penalties relating to the Common Agricultural Policy as a result of the return to paper-assisted digital applications in 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437146","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>The new Common Agricultural Policy has been widely recognised as being more complex for farmers to understand and harder for Member States to administer. The new schemes have not yet been audited by the European Commission so it is too early to say what the level of any disallowance will be, but complexity tends to increase disallowance risk.</p><br /><p>For the Basic Payment Scheme 2015 the Rural Payments Agency (RPA) sent pre-populated claim forms to farmers and land owners to allow them to submit their applications before the deadline. The RPA provided an unprecedented level of support to farmers and land owners through the Rural Payments Helpline and 50 Drop In Centres that allowed some 88,000 applications to be received within the deadline. ‘Paper-assisted’ means that forms were completed on paper but then entered on to a digital system by RPA staff.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437146/answer",,,,,"19642","2015-12-15T12:46:06.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437146/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437146/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the definition of paper-assisted digital applications is for the Common Agricultural Policy Delivery Programme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437147","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-16","<p>All movements of puppies into the UK that are not covered by the Pet Travel Scheme are subject to the provisions of the Council Directive 92/65/EEC (Balai Directive). This is implemented by the Trade in Animal and Related Products Regulations 2011. Commercial movements of puppies may be subject to a post-import check at the place of final destination by the Animal and Plant Health Agency.</p><br /><p>Responsibility for enforcing the Trade in Animal and Related Products Regulations 2011 falls to local authorities. They are also responsible for enforcing welfare in transport legislation which makes it an offence for anyone to transport animals or cause animals to be transported in a way likely to cause injury or unnecessary suffering to them.</p><br /><p>The act of smuggling puppies in contravention of the animal health and welfare requirements may give rise to the commission of a number of different criminal offences depending on the circumstances of the illegal import. Defra is working with interested parties with a particular interest in improving the collection, analysis and use of intelligence relating to this illegal trade. We are also aware that some EU countries, such as the Republic of Ireland, have recently tightened up their regulatory requirements for puppy breeding, which we hope will also have a positive impact on the problem of illegal trade.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437147/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T08:46:50.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437147/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437147/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Dogs: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to tackle the illegal transport of farmed puppies from the Republic of Ireland and southern Europe into the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437148","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2015-12-18","<p>The table below shows how much the Environment Agency spent directly on maintaining flood defences in the years requested:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Allocation £m</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Asset Management</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>156</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>147</p></td><td><p>171</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Government has confirmed that flood maintenance funding will be protected in real terms for the duration of this Parliament.</p><p><ins class="ministerial">In addition to the maintenance spend, a further £2.3 Billion will be invested in flood defences in the next six years, providing better protection to over 300,000 households.</ins></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437148/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T11:14:44.87Z","2016-02-04T11:26:08.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437148/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437148/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437148/answer/previousversion/36488","Biography information for Rory Stewart","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2015 to Question 16031, how much the Environment Agency spent directly on maintaining flood defences in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13 and (d) 2013-14; and how much the agency projects it will spend on such defences in (i) 2015-16, (ii) 2016-17, (iii) 2017-18, (iv) 2018-19 and (v) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437149","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government has committed to protect flood maintenance funding in real terms over the course of this Parliament.</p><br /><p>The Environment Agency does not record the number of personnel working solely on maintaining flood defences, as the relevant staff undertake a number of activities, including both operating and maintaining defences. Maintenance may also be performed by third parties.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437149/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-21T13:38:24.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437149/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437149/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many full-time equivalent Environment Agency staff were employed on maintenance of flood defences on 1 April (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014 and (f) 2015.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437150","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2015-12-16","<br /><p>The Environment Agency's Long Term Investment Scenarios report represents the best currently available projections of potential long term costs to manage flood and coastal risk under a range of scenarios reflecting future uncertainties. It will be kept under review as any further evidence emerges.</p><br /><p>The report confirms that current Government investment plans to 2020, together with forecast local contributions, are in line with the level the Environment Agency’s assessment indicates is necessary to reduce overall flood risk <del class="ministerial">by 5%</del>.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437150/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T15:36:34.807Z","2015-12-16T16:15:12.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437150/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437150/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437150/answer/previousversion/35407","Biography information for Rory Stewart","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the Environment Agency's 2014 Long Term Investment Scenarios recommended optimum overall investment in flood defences of £750m to £800m each year to 2019-20; and whether she expects that level of overall investment to be achieved.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437151","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-16","<p>In the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 we reiterated our commitment to invest £2.3 billion in more than 1,500 projects by 2021. This funding will help better protect 300,000 homes. We also announced our commitment to protect flood maintenance spending in real terms over this Parliament.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437151/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T15:40:20.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437151/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437151/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what measures in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 will affect the level of funding for flood defences up to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437152","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-18","<p>Defra’s core climate change adaptation team of eight officials is coordinating and inputting to the preparation of the second Climate Change Risk Assessment, to be laid in Parliament in January 2017. Many other officials from across Defra, wider Government and its agencies are also contributing to the assessment. The underlying evidence report that will make up the bulk of the assessment is being prepared by the Adaptation Sub-Committee of the Committee on Climate Change, with extensive input from around 100 other experts.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437152/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T13:18:22.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437152/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437152/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many of her officials are engaged in preparing the Government's next Climate Change Risk Assessment.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437153","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2015-12-18","<p>The table below shows how much the Environment Agency spent directly on maintaining flood defences in the years requested:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Allocation £m</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Asset Management</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>156</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>147</p></td><td><p>171</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>The Government has confirmed that flood maintenance funding will be protected in real terms for the duration of this Parliament.</p><br /><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p><ins class="ministerial">In addition to the maintenance spend, a further £2.3 Billion will be invested in flood defences in the next six years, providing better protection to over 300,000 households.</ins></p></ins></p> <br /> <br />","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437153/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T11:14:44.787Z","2015-12-18T11:39:58.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437153/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437153/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437153/answer/previousversion/35561","Biography information for Rory Stewart","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-10","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 December 2015 to Question 18118, when she plans to announce the level of funding for flood defence maintenance in each year until 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437154","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) Ministers aim to respond to all correspondence from Honourable Members within 20 working days of receipt. However, due to the complex nature of certain items of correspondence, it is not always possible to meet this deadline.</p><p>FCO Ministers responded to around 81 per cent of correspondence from parliamentarians between 1 January and 30 September 2015 within 20 working days. During this period, FCO Ministers sent a total of 5702 letters to Members of Parliament, Peers and Members of the Public.</p><p>Detailed information on the average time taken to respond to correspondence is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437154/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T16:48:41.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437154/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437154/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437154/answer/previousversion/35754","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's target is for time taken to respond to letters and emails from hon. Members; what the average time taken by his Department to respond to such letters and emails is; and how many such letters and emails received between 1 January and 30 September 2015 remained unanswered after eight weeks.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437155","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) received the letter from the hon. Member for Rutherglen and Hamilton West (Margaret Ferrier) on 27 November 2015. The Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood) will respond to the hon. Member by 24 December.</p><p>FCO Ministers aim to respond to all correspondence from Members of this House, both written and electronic, within 20 working days of receipt, in line with Cabinet Office guidance.</p><p><br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/441892/Cabinet_Office_Guidance_on_correspondence.pdf</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437155/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T18:05:03.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437155/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437155/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he plans to reply to the letter of 26 November 2015 from the hon. Member for Rutherglen and Hamilton West regarding mass executions in Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","19623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437156","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) 2014 Annual Human Rights and Democracy Report stated that we have an estimated 240 full-time equivalents who work directly on human rights. That number included two contracted Human Rights Advisers within the Human Rights and Democracy Department in London, and two Human Rights Advisers at the UK Mission in Geneva. However, as the Foreign Secretary explained in his Independent article on 10 December, [http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/promoting-human-rights-is-not-about-who-can-shout-the-loudest-a6767386.html], human rights work is not just the preserve of a few specialised staff but the responsibility of all British diplomats and an important part of the training our staff receive.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437156/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T18:03:17.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437156/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437156/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Diplomatic Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which UK embassies have a human rights adviser on their staff.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","19577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437157","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>Since the debate on 5 November my Department has not received any representations from any diplomatic missions in the UK on the dog meat trade, nor have Ministers made representations to their counterparts abroad. As highlighted during the debate by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), I am contacting our Ambassadors in the countries concerned to review our activities in this area.</p><p>The Government is committed to raising the standards of animal welfare at home and abroad. I raised animal welfare issues during my visit to the region in February and will continue to make representations when appropriate.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437157/answer",,,,,"19549 ; 19550","2015-12-15T17:51:06.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437157/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437157/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Dogs: Meat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has received from diplomatic representatives in the UK of states where the trade of dog meat for consumption is active subsequent to the debate in the House on the dog meat trade of 5 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","19548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437158","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>Since the debate on 5 November my Department has not received any representations from any diplomatic missions in the UK on the dog meat trade, nor have Ministers made representations to their counterparts abroad. As highlighted during the debate by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), I am contacting our Ambassadors in the countries concerned to review our activities in this area.</p><p>The Government is committed to raising the standards of animal welfare at home and abroad. I raised animal welfare issues during my visit to the region in February and will continue to make representations when appropriate.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437158/answer",,,,,"19548 ; 19550","2015-12-15T17:51:06.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437158/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437158/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Dogs: Meat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Ministers have made to their counterparts abroad or to their diplomatic representatives in the UK on the practice of consuming and selling dog meat for consumption subsequent to the debate in the House on the dog meat trade of 5 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","19549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437159","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>Since the debate on 5 November my Department has not received any representations from any diplomatic missions in the UK on the dog meat trade, nor have Ministers made representations to their counterparts abroad. As highlighted during the debate by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), I am contacting our Ambassadors in the countries concerned to review our activities in this area.</p><p>The Government is committed to raising the standards of animal welfare at home and abroad. I raised animal welfare issues during my visit to the region in February and will continue to make representations when appropriate.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437159/answer",,,,,"19548 ; 19549","2015-12-15T17:51:06.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437159/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437159/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Dogs: Meat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department has taken or plans to take on the practice of consuming and selling dog meat for consumption in addition to the steps he set out in the debate in the House on the dog meat trade of 5 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","19550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437160","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>We are aware of reports on alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law (IHL) in Yemen by the Coalition, including alleged airstrikes resulting in civilian, including child casualties and damage to civilian infrastructure, and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised our concerns with the Saudi Arabian authorities and received assurances that they are complying with IHL. We continue to engage with Saudi Arabia on those assurances and have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with IHL.</p><p>We are also concerned by reports of alleged IHL violations by Houthi-Saleh and pro-government forces, including attacks on civilians in Aden and Taiz; intimidation of UN ships attempting to dock at Aden; the use of schools and hospitals for military purposes; the use of child soldiers; and the targeting of aid workers and restrictions on humanitarian access. We have also raised the importance of compliance with IHL with the Houthis.</p><p>The UK operates one of the most rigorous and transparent export control regimes in the world. All exports of arms and controlled military goods to Saudi Arabia are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Licensing Criteria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437160/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T13:51:05.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437160/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437160/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-10","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will issue a response to Early Day Motion 846, Use of explosive weapons and human rights violations in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","19536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437161","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>No discussions have taken place between Ministers of the Department and the Northern Ireland Executive on improving access to high-quality services for people affected by Parkinson's disease.</p><br /><p>As health is a devolved matter these issues are not regularly discussed between Ministers and their counterparts in the devolved administrations, however research and evidence of best practice is made widely available throughout the United Kingdom.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437161/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T14:31:54.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437161/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Parkinson's Disease: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on improving access to high-quality services for people affected by Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","19509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437162","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>The information is not held centrally.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437162/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T14:13:14.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437162/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Weather: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the NHS was of treating cold-related admissions to hospitals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","19510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437163","Department of Health","false","2015-12-16","<p>In England, eye clinics and their staffing, including Eye Clinic Liaison Officers (ECLO), are commissioned and funded by individual clinical commissioning groups on the basis of local assessments of need.</p><p /> <p>The Department does not collect data on the number of eye clinic liaison officers employed in hospitals or how much has been spent on funding ECLOs.</p><p /> <p>The Government fully appreciates the impact that sight loss can have on a person’s life and the importance of information being available for those newly diagnosed with sight loss, including signposting patients to appropriate support and rehabilitation services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437163/answer",,,,,"19512","2015-12-16T17:57:57.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437163/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Visual Impairment: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many full-time sight loss adviser posts there are in hospitals in England.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","19511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437164","Department of Health","false","2015-12-16","<p>In England, eye clinics and their staffing, including Eye Clinic Liaison Officers (ECLO), are commissioned and funded by individual clinical commissioning groups on the basis of local assessments of need.</p><p /> <p>The Department does not collect data on the number of eye clinic liaison officers employed in hospitals or how much has been spent on funding ECLOs.</p><p /> <p>The Government fully appreciates the impact that sight loss can have on a person’s life and the importance of information being available for those newly diagnosed with sight loss, including signposting patients to appropriate support and rehabilitation services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437164/answer",,,,,"19511","2015-12-16T17:57:58.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437164/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Visual Impairment: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been spent on the provision of eye clinic care liaison officers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","19512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437165","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>From 1 August 2017, new nursing, midwifery and allied health students will no longer receive NHS bursaries. Instead, they will have access to the same student loans system as other students.</p><br /><p>We intend that students studying nursing, midwifery and the allied health subjects as a second degree will also be able to get student loans.</p><br /><p>The change will only affect new students commencing their courses from 1 August 2017.</p><p>We plan to run a consultation in early 2016 to ask how we can successfully deliver the reforms.</p><br /><p>Under the loans system, students on nursing, midwifery and allied health courses will receive around a 25% increase in the financial support available to them for living costs. The precise change for individuals will be dependent on their circumstances – for example, where they study, the length of the course, income and residency.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437165/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:17:35.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437165/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of finance options available to student nurses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","19564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437166","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>We have provided £3.2 million in funding in 2015/16 to the Time to Change programme to support the excellent work the programme does in reducing the stigma associated with mental illness.</p><br /><p>The Time to Change programme received £16 million in funding from Government between 2011/12 and 2014/15.</p><br /><p>Officials are in discussions with Time to Change, and its other funding partners, about the next phase of the programme.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437166/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T12:33:57.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437166/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Mental Illness: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons he has not yet announced funding for the Time to Change campaigns beyond March 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","19556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437167","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Department for Education and NHS England have commissioned Ecorys to undertake an independent evaluation of the Mental Health Services and School Link Pilots. The evaluation will run from October 2015 to November 2016, covering all 22 pilot sites with Ecorys formally reporting back to the Department for Education and NHS England towards the end of 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437167/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T12:22:59.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437167/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437167/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Mental Health Services: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to report on the progress of the pilot being run in conjunction with the Department for Education to give schools access to a single point of contact for mental health.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","19557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437168","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>We recognise that young carers may have particular vulnerabilities and are more likely to develop mental health problems because they fulfil that caregiver role.</p><br /><p>That is why the local transformation planning process, currently being implemented by every clinical commissioning group across England, will be so important. Local Transformation Plans establish an integrated whole system approach to driving the improvements children and young people want, with the NHS, public health, voluntary and community, local authority children’s services, education and youth justice sectors working together to provide improved support to those children and young people who have a mental health need or who as a young carer might be more likely to develop a mental health need.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437168/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T12:31:24.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437168/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437168/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Carers: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve the mental health of young carers and young adult carers as part of the Future in Mind policy.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","19558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437169","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Department has no plans to make any such assessment.</p><p /> <p>Research undertaken by the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD) found that, compared to the average employee, zero hours contract workers are just as satisfied with their job (65% versus 63%) and happier with their work-life balance (62% versus 58%).</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437169/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:46:46.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437169/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437169/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Zero Hours Contracts: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the effects of zero-hour and uncertain hour contracts on the mental health of people holding such contracts.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","19559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437170","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has announced that the new Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) assessment framework being developed by NHS England will contain six key clinical areas, including mental health. The framework will be published in March 2016 and will be operational from 1 April 2016.</p><br /><p>An annual assessment of these clinical areas will be moderated by independent panels of experts. Paul Farmer, Chief Executive of MIND, has been appointed panel chair for mental health.</p><br /><p>A first simple assessment of all CCGs in these six areas will be published in June 2016. The formal annual summative assessment of all CCGs for 2016/17 will happen at the end of that financial year and be published in summer 2017. The annual assessment will be based on a four point scale of outstanding, good, requires improvement and inadequate.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437170/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T12:25:11.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437170/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437170/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Mental Health Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish details of his proposal to introduce Ofsted-style ratings for clinical commissioning groups' mental health services.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","19560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437171","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>There are a number of inherited cardiac conditions. These include familial hypercholesterolaemia (FH) (which leads to premature cardiac disease and reduction in life expectancy), and conditions which increase the risk of sudden cardiac death.</p><p>The responsibility for commissioning FH services lies with local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). Provision of services will take into account the needs of the population overall.</p><p>NICE has published a guideline on the identification and management of FH which includes recommendations that children at risk because they have a parent with FH should have diagnostic tests before the age of 10. The national clinical director (NCD) for heart disease at NHS England is working to promote cascade testing for the relatives of people who have hypercholesterolaemia. NHS England’s NCD has also worked closely with the British Heart Foundation in their appointment of FH Nurses to undertake genetic testing, and with the other major charity in this field - HEART-UK.</p><p>NHS England is working closely with Public Health England (PHE) to identify the barriers to FH testing (and cholesterol management in general) with the support of the British Heart Foundation and a great deal is now being done to raise the profile of this condition, break down the barriers to genetic testing and provide better management of the condition.</p><p>With regards to those conditions which may raise the risk of sudden cardiac death, the National Screening Committee concluded that a national screening programme was not appropriate. However, children who are taken on by football clubs for formal youth training do undergo cardiac screening as do a number of professional sports participants.</p><p>A recent review concluded that childhood obesity not only increases cardiovascular risk in adulthood, but it is also associated with cardiovascular damage during childhood.</p><br /><p>To identify and support children classified as obese and therefore at risk of cardiovascular disease, PHE oversees delivery of England’s National Child Measurement programme (NCMP). NCMP provides robust local and national data on child weight status to inform health service planning and engage families through the provision of feedback of results to parents. Local authorities are provided with guidance to support the delivery of the NCMP programme and encouraged to sign post parents to local weight management services where possible.</p><br /><p>The programme covers children in Reception (ages 4-5 years) and Year 6 (ages 10-11 years), and is now a mandated public health function of local authorities.</p><br /><p>There is also strong evidence for a positive association between physical activity and cardio-metabolic health among school aged children, with higher levels of physical activity associated with higher levels of cardiovascular and metabolic health.</p><p>PHE is working to support children to adhere to healthy eating guidelines and meet the Chief Medical Officer’s physical activity guidelines through a number of approaches including through its flagship Change4Life programme and the development and implementation of the framework, ‘Everybody Active, Everyday’ at national and local level. This framework sets out a long term, evidence-based approach to embed physical activity into daily life.</p><br /> <br /> <br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437171/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T13:29:46.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437171/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437171/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Heart Diseases: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department plans to take to (a) identify and (b) support young people at risk of cardiac problems.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","19585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437172","Department of Health","false","2015-12-16","<p>NHS England’s Planning Guidance for 2015/16,<em> Forward View into action: planning for 2015-16,</em> sets out the expectation that clinical commissioning groups’ (CCGs) spending on mental health services in 2015/16 should increase in real terms, and grow by at least as much as each CCG’s allocation increase to support the ambition of parity between mental and physical health. Compliance with the Planning Guidance is being assured at national and Area Team level.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437172/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T18:02:46.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437172/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437172/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that funding is sufficient to meet patient demand in (a) community mental healthcare and (b) inpatient mental healthcare; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","19583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437173","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified 40 items of correspondence expressing concerns about Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust. This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><br /><p>In 2014, NHS England initiated action including an investigation of the deaths of all patients of the trust who had been in receipt of mental health or learning disability services since 2011.</p><br /><p>We are advised by NHS England that a first draft of the Mazars report was shared with it and Southern Health Foundation Trust in September 2015. The Department has not received a copy of the report and the report is still to be finalised before publication.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437173/answer",,,,,"19687","2015-12-15T17:48:19.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437173/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437173/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations his Department has received (a) since his appointment as Secretary of State and (b) since the appointment of his predecessor in that post expressing concerns about Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","19686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437174","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified 40 items of correspondence expressing concerns about Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust. This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><br /><p>In 2014, NHS England initiated action including an investigation of the deaths of all patients of the trust who had been in receipt of mental health or learning disability services since 2011.</p><br /><p>We are advised by NHS England that a first draft of the Mazars report was shared with it and Southern Health Foundation Trust in September 2015. The Department has not received a copy of the report and the report is still to be finalised before publication.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437174/answer",,,,,"19686","2015-12-15T17:48:19.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437174/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437174/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when (a) his Department, (b) NHS England and (c) Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust first received a copy of the Mazers report on Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","19687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437175","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>Over the course of the Spending Review there have been a large number of in-depth discussions at both official and Ministerial level to inform the outcome. These discussions and analysis informed the decision to provide a settlement which means local government has access to the funding it needs to increase social care spending in real terms by the end of the Parliament, including:</p><br /><p>- The introduction of a social care precept, which puts money raising powers into the hands of local areas who understand the need in their area and who are best placed to respond. This could raise up to £2 billion by the end of the Parliament; and</p><p>- From 2017/18, additional funds for social care will be made available through the Better Care Fund. This will rise to £1.5 billion by 2019/20.</p><br /><p>Following this additional funding, we expect councils will be able to increase the prices they pay for care in order to cover costs providers are facing such as the national living wage.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437175/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T12:29:03.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437175/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437175/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Social Services: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on making additional funding available to local authorities to help fund the introduction of the national living wage into social care from April 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","19646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437176","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Department has been reviewing the rent arrangements NHS Property Services inherited from primary care trusts in April 2013, with a view to moving towards a more rational charging policy. It is estimated around 900 general practitioner practices would pay increased rental charges for their premises if NHS Property Services moves to market value rents. Rental costs would be reimbursable in the normal way in accordance with the NHS ‘premises costs’ directions.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437176/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:09:15.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437176/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437176/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","GP Surgeries: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of GP surgeries which will pay increased rental charges for their premises after NHS Property Services Ltd moves to market value rents; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437177","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>Patients who are not ‘ordinarily resident’ in the United Kingdom and to whom no exemption from charges under the Charging Regulations applies should be directly charged.</p><br /><p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for funding the care of those visitors to the UK who are exempt from charges and those services that are free to all overseas visitors. Data are not collected centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437177/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T13:25:39.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437177/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437177/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust received for treating people from outside the EU in (a) 2011, (b) 2012, (c) 2013 and (d) 2014.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437178","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>There have been no discussions between Health Ministers and Harrow Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on this matter.</p><p>NHS England has advised us that there are already two practices offering walk-in appointments in the west of the Harrow CCG area. We understand that the CCG is planning to establish a third primary care hub with the same service specification in the east of the Borough.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437178/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T15:10:47.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437178/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437178/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Health Centres: Harrow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions Ministers of his Department have had with Harrow Clinical Commissioning Group about providing a polyclinic in the eastern part of the London Borough of Harrow; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437179","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>These estimates are a matter for HM Treasury.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437179/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T17:54:48.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437179/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437179/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437179/answer/previousversion/35761","Biography information for Alistair Burt","17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Social Services: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of introducing the national living wage into social care from April 2016.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","19638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437180","Department of Health","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Chief Inspector of Hospitals Inspection within the Care Quality Commission (CQC) in May 2014 rated the Brighton and Sussex University Hospital Trust as “Requires Improvement”. In 2015 the CQC rated the Trust as ‘Inadequate’. The Trust is urgently implementing the action recommended.</p><p /> <p>In addition, the Trust is actively engaged with the Emergency Care Improvement Programme to ensure that the Trust can deliver the accident and emergency standard by March 2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437180/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:39:17.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437180/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437180/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the performance of Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust services.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","19639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437181","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<br /><p>The Spending Review announced on 25 November the level of funding that the NHS in England would receive by 2020-21. The NHS will be receiving £10 billion more per year in real terms by 2020-21 than in 2014-15, which fully funds the NHS’ own plan – the ‘Five Year Forward View’. £6 billion of that £10 billion will be delivered by 2016-17. This is set out in the attached table.</p><br /><p>The exact budget profile for NHS England will be set out in the Mandate to NHS England, due to be published shortly.</p><br /><p>Under the Barnett Formula, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland receive a population-based proportion of changes in planned spending on comparable United Kingdom Government services in England. Changes in each devolved administration’s spending allocation, is determined by:</p><br /><p>- the quantity of the change in planned spending in departments of the United Kingdom Government; and</p><p>- the extent to which the relevant United Kingdom programme is comparable with the services carried out by each devolved administration and each country’s population proportion.</p><br /><p>The allocation of public expenditure between the services, including health, under the control of the devolved administrations is for the devolved administrations to determine.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437181/answer","England NHS budget for each year to 2020-21.docx","England NHS budget for each year to 2020-21.docx","England NHS budget for each year to 2020-21","England NHS budget for each year to 2020-21",,"2015-12-17T14:59:03.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437181/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437181/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-10","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how the Government plans to phase increases to funding for NHS England over the next five years; and what the Barnett consequentials of decisions on such phasing will be.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437182","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Common Travel Area between the UK, Ireland and the Crown Dependencies and the free movement of goods within the EU mean that close liaison and co-operation between UK and Irish law enforcement partners against serious and organised crime is both vital and valued by both sides. The National Crime Agency has dedicated resources currently working with Irish law enforcement agencies to tackle the threat from organised crime that affects both our countries.</p><p>On 17 November 2015, the Northern Ireland Office published ‘A Fresh Start: The Stormont Agreement and Implementation Plan’. The National Crime Agency will be involved in discussions with the Department of Justice for Northern Ireland, the Northern Ireland Office, the Police Service of Northern Ireland, Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs and Immigration Enforcement in relation to the implementation of the agreement.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437182/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:19:53.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437182/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437182/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Organised Crime: Northern Ireland and Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what level of co-operation there is between the National Crime Agency and authorities in the Republic of Ireland on combatting organised criminal activities taking place between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","19694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437183","Home Office","false","2016-01-04","<p>The Government welcomes research into modern slavery, including the work that St Mary’s University is undertaking on behalf of the Santa Marta Group. The Home Office has no record that either Ministers or its officials played any part in the selection process.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437183/answer",,,,,,"2016-01-04T14:11:40.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437183/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437183/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Slavery: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons she selected St Mary's University, Twickenham, to host a specialist international centre for research into modern slavery and human trafficking; and whether any other institution was considered for this role.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","19620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437184","Home Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Home Office does not hold the requested information on the number of persons in custody for terrorism-related offences and domestic extremism/separatism who were (a) charged with and (b) convicted of offences, broken down by self-declared religion.</p><p>Table P.02 of the statistical bulletin ‘Operation of police powers under the Terrorism Act 2000 and subsequent legislation: Arrests, outcomes, and stop and search, Great Britain, quarterly update to September 2015’ contains statistics on the number of persons in custody for terrorism-related offences and domestic extremism/separatism by type of prisoner. This includes those who have been remanded, convicted, as well as deportation cases, broken down by self-defined ethnicity.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437184/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T17:34:04.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437184/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437184/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Terrorism: Arrests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of those listed in table P.04 of the September 2015 Statistical Bulletin 04/15, Operation of police powers under the Terrorism Act 2000 and subsequent legislation: Arrests, outcomes and stop and search, Great Britain, financial year ending 31 March 2015, were (a) charged with and (b) convicted of offences.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437185","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>Target times for replying to correspondence from hon. Members differ in operational and non-operational areas of the Home Office. Information for the period 1 January to 30 September 2015 is included in the attached table. Across the department correspondence unanswered after eight weeks is approximately 0.3% of that received.</p><table><tbody><tr><td></td><td><p>Volume</p></td><td><p>Target</p></td><td><p>Average response time</p></td><td><p>Unanswered after 8 weeks</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK Visas and Immigration, Immigration Enforcement and Border Force</p></td><td><p>25,111</p></td><td><p>20 working days</p></td><td><p>9 working days</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Home Office HQ</p></td><td><p>4,608</p></td><td><p>15 working days</p></td><td><p>11 working days</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HM Passport Office</p></td><td><p>2,522</p></td><td><p>15 working days</p></td><td><p>12 working days</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437185/answer","Table - PQ 19652 (Mark Hendrick MP).docx","Table - PQ 19652 (Mark Hendrick MP).docx","Table - PQ 19652 ","Table - PQ 19652 ",,"2015-12-15T17:42:42.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437185/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437185/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437185/answer/previousversion/35663","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Home Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's target is for time taken to respond to letters and emails from hon. Members; what the average time taken by her Department to respond to such letters and emails is; and how many such letters and emails received between 1 January and 30 September 2015 remained unanswered after eight weeks.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437186","Home Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>We have an excellent offer for international students who wish to study at our world-leading institutions and there remains no limit on the number who can do so. As a result, the UK remains the second most popular destination in the world for international higher education students, and our excellent universities continue to attract large volumes of overseas students.</p><p>Annual visa applications from international students to study at British universities are now 17 per cent higher than they were in 2010, with visa applications to our elite Russell Group universities up by 39 per cent since 2010.</p><p>The most recent figures produced by the Higher Education Statistics Agency also show a 6 per cent increase in the number of full-time non-EU new enrolments to UK higher education institutions between 2012/13 and 2013/14.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437186/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T17:43:35.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437186/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437186/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the Government's immigration policies on the number of international students enrolling in UK universities.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437187","Home Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>The ferry crossings between Stranraer, Cairnryan and Northern Ireland are domestic routes and are therefore not subject to immigration border controls.</p><p>Home Office Immigration Enforcement in Northern Ireland and Police Scotland work in close partnership to detect illegal migrants who are already in the UK and travelling on these ferries. Detections have increased year on year since the current partnership arrangement was introduced in 2011.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437187/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-16T17:42:12.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437187/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437187/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","UK Border Force: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the implications of its decision to remove border staff at the ports of Stranraer and Cairnryan for UK security.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437188","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The following table shows, for each year from November 2010 to October 2015, both the average end-to-end turnaround time for Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) certificates and the average time to complete the Police National Computer (PNC) stage.</p><p>The PNC stage has been defined as the time spent in DBS between receipt of an application and – in the case of Enhanced Disclosures – its despatch to local police forces; or – in the case of Standard Disclosures – its assembly for return to the applicant. During this period, DBS conducts a search of the Police National Computer, followed by internal checks to ensure both the accuracy and quality of certificates.</p><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Time Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average End to End Turnaround (days)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average PNC Stage Turnaround (days)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-10 to Oct-11</p></td><td><p>16.22</p></td><td><p>1.72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-11 to Oct-12</p></td><td><p>10.85</p></td><td><p>2.25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-12 to Oct-13</p></td><td><p>10.23</p></td><td><p>1.54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-13 to Oct-14</p></td><td><p>13.63</p></td><td><p>2.42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-14 to Oct-15</p></td><td><p>14.28</p></td><td><p>2.86</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437188/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:16:28.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437188/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437188/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Vetting: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, (a) what the average waiting time was for checks by the Disclosure and Barring Service to be completed and (b) how long on average the Police National Computer search took in (i) 2010-11, (ii) 2011-12, (iii) 2012-13, (iv) 2013-14, (v) 2014-15 and (vi) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437189","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>This information is not held centrally. Information about the number of cases under investigation may be obtainable from the individual force.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437189/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:28:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437189/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437189/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Fraud: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many serious fraud cases are under investigation by Merseyside Police Force; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437190","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government and police work nationally, and with international partners, to reduce the threat to the UK from the criminal use of firearms. In 2013/14, firearms were used in a small and diminishing proportion of total police recorded crime, 0.2%. We also support local areas to take action against gang violence to reduce offending and protect vulnerable people. Under the Ending Gang and Youth Violence programme, Birmingham was subject to a peer review in 2012 and has implemented and integrated the recommendations from the review into their local strategic plans. The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of arrests made in connection with gun crime. The UK has some of the toughest gun laws in the world and the government and the police continue to work together to reduce the threat from the criminal use of firearms. We will be reviewing options to strengthen the current legislation to ensure it safeguards against abuse by criminals following representations made by the police (and other stakeholders) during the Law Commission’s scoping consultation on firearms legislation. The number of offences involving firearms (excluding air weapons) in the West Midlands has fallen by 40% since 2010, from 903 offences in 2009/10 to 540 in 2013/14.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437190/answer",,,,,"19628","2015-12-15T17:18:26.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437190/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437190/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Firearms: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many arrests have been made in connection with gun crime in the West Midlands metropolitan area in (a) each of the last 10 years and (b) each quarter of 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Khalid Mahmood","Birmingham, Perry Barr","Mr Khalid Mahmood","19626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437191","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government and police work nationally, and with international partners, to reduce the threat to the UK from the criminal use of firearms. In 2013/14, firearms were used in a small and diminishing proportion of total police recorded crime, 0.2%.</p><p>The Government keeps the firearms licensing system under review to safeguard against abuse by criminals and to preserve public safety. We have asked the Law Commission to conduct a scoping consultation on firearms law and we are considering the recommendations made by HM Inspectorate of Constabulary following their inspection on how the firearms system is working in practice. We also support local areas to take action against gang violence to reduce offending and protect vulnerable people. Under the Ending Gang and Youth Violence programme, Birmingham was subject to a peer review in 2012 and has implemented and integrated the recommendations from the review into their local strategic plans.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437191/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:14:47.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437191/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437191/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Firearms: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle gang-related gun crime.","false","Biography information for Mr Khalid Mahmood","Birmingham, Perry Barr","Mr Khalid Mahmood","19627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437192","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government and police work nationally, and with international partners, to reduce the threat to the UK from the criminal use of firearms. In 2013/14, firearms were used in a small and diminishing proportion of total police recorded crime, 0.2%. We also support local areas to take action against gang violence to reduce offending and protect vulnerable people. Under the Ending Gang and Youth Violence programme, Birmingham was subject to a peer review in 2012 and has implemented and integrated the recommendations from the review into their local strategic plans. The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of arrests made in connection with gun crime. The UK has some of the toughest gun laws in the world and the government and the police continue to work together to reduce the threat from the criminal use of firearms. We will be reviewing options to strengthen the current legislation to ensure it safeguards against abuse by criminals following representations made by the police (and other stakeholders) during the Law Commission’s scoping consultation on firearms legislation. The number of offences involving firearms (excluding air weapons) in the West Midlands has fallen by 40% since 2010, from 903 offences in 2009/10 to 540 in 2013/14.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437192/answer",,,,,"19626","2015-12-15T17:18:26.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437192/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437192/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Firearms: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to support the West Midlands Police Force respond to an increase in the levels of gun crime in Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Mr Khalid Mahmood","Birmingham, Perry Barr","Mr Khalid Mahmood","19628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437193","Home Office","false","2015-12-18","<p>Section 48(7) of the Modern Slavery Act requires the Government to lay before Parliament a report setting out the steps it proposes to take in relation to independent child trafficking advocates within nine months of Royal Assent of the Modern Slavery Act. The Government will publish this report and the independent evaluation, by the final day that Parliament sits this year.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437193/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T15:16:20.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437193/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437193/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Human Trafficking: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress her Department has made on the evaluation of the Child Trafficking Advocates Trial.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","19582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437194","Home Office","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Prime Minister made clear in his immigration speech of 21 May that the Government intends to roll out the Right to Rent scheme across the whole of the UK. The roll out is being taken forward in a phased manner. Having started in a part of the West Midlands, the next phase will extend the scheme across the rest of England as of 1 February 2016. The Government intends to roll out the scheme to the rest of the UK thereafter as part of the final phase. In relation to the provisions that relate to the private rented sector in the Immigration Bill 2015-16, the Bill also enables for these provisions to be enacted across Scotland at a later date.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437194/answer",,,,,"19568","2016-01-05T14:19:03.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437194/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437194/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Private Rented Housing: Undocumented Migrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Right to Rent Scheme for landlords to perform immigration checks on tenants will come into force in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","19590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437195","Home Office","false","2015-12-14","<p>Asylum Operations has existing processes that ensure claimants and legal representatives have contact details should they wish to discuss case progression. In addition, all claimants and representatives are kept informed should an initial decision on their asylum claim be delayed, with this correspondence outlining the reason for delay and providing an approximate timescale as to when a decision can be expected.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437195/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-14T17:26:23.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437195/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437195/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Asylum: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will set up a dedicated correspondence team in her Department to liaise with applicants solicitors on the processing of asylum claims.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","19574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437196","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. The Ministry of Justice are responsible for statistics on convictions.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437196/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:25:55.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437196/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437196/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Fraud: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many convictions resulted from reports to Action Fraud in each year since it was set up.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","19578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437197","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>The evidence to support this statement has derived from analysis by the National Crime Agency of investigations involving their National Cyber Crime Unit. This found the average age of suspects to be 17, compared to 24 in the previous year. The statement has also been informed by debriefing sessions that the National Cyber Crime Unit has undertaken with offenders, and academic engagement.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437197/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:34:25.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437197/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437197/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Cybercrime: Young Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the page on the National Crime Agency website entitled, Cyber crime: Preventing young people from getting involved, what the statistical evidence is for the statement that more and more teenagers and young people are involved in cyber crime.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","19544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437198","Home Office","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Prime Minister made clear in his immigration speech of 21 May that the Government intends to roll out the Right to Rent scheme across the whole of the UK. The roll out is being taken forward in a phased manner. Having started in a part of the West Midlands, the next phase will extend the scheme across the rest of England as of 1 February 2016. The Government intends to roll out the scheme to the rest of the UK thereafter as part of the final phase. In relation to the provisions that relate to the private rented sector in the Immigration Bill 2015-16, the Bill also enables for these provisions to be enacted across Scotland at a later date.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437198/answer",,,,,"19590","2016-01-05T14:19:03.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437198/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437198/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Immigration Bill: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the residential tenancy provisions of the Immigration Bill would come into force in Scotland if enacted.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","19568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437199","Home Office","false","2015-12-18","<p>I refer my Hon. Friend to my response of 11 November 2015 [14823]. Between 31 July 2014 and 31 July 2015 849 contacts were made to the NSPCC-run modern slavery helpline and of these 272 referrals were made to the police. The Home Office does not maintain a record of how many victims were identified as a result of these referrals.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437199/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-18T15:25:45.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437199/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437199/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Human Trafficking: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many victims of human trafficking have been identified and their identities subsequently forwarded to the police as a result of people calling the NSPCC human trafficking and slavery helpline between July 2014 and June 2015.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","19542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437200","Home Office","false","2015-12-15","<p>UK citizens can submit visa applications on behalf of relatives living overseas via the following website - www.visa4uk.fco.gov.uk/home/welcome.</p><p>The applicant would then need to travel to their nearest Visa Application Centre (VAC) to verify the information provided and progress their application to the next stage.</p><p>There are no VACs in Yemen; guidance for applying for a UK visa from Yemen can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/yemen-apply-for-a-uk-visa/apply-for-a-uk-visa-in-yemen</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437200/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:27:18.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437200/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437200/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-10","Visas: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how UK citizens living in the UK can apply for a visa for relatives living in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","19523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437201","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-17","<p>I flew to the COP 21 once which was the most cost effective and efficient means of travel. DFID offsets all its air and train travel.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437201/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-17T17:34:56.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437201/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437201/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Climate Change Convention: Paris","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what form of transport she used to travel to the COP21 conference in Paris in December 2015; and for what reasons she used that form of transport.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437202","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-15","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region. We have pledged over £1.1 billion to date, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. This makes us the second largest bilateral donor. Of this total, the UK has allocated £561 million to support vulnerable people inside Syria to date.</p><p>By the end of June 2015, UK support inside Syria had provided over 15.1 million food rations; access to clean water for over 1.6 million people (peak month); 2 million medical consultations; more than 4 million relief packages; and there have been over 6.9 million instances when people benefited from sanitation and hygiene activities. We are also helping those who feel safe to do so to stay in Syria by building their ability to cope, helping the moderate opposition to provide governance and essential services, and supporting the provision of education and jobs.</p><br /><p>The UK will continue to punch above its weight in supporting the reconstruction of Syria. That is why, on 26 November, the Prime Minister signalled that the UK will commit at least £1 billion to Syria’s reconstruction in the longer term.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437202/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T16:37:04.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437202/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437202/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential contribution of aid to Syria to strengthening the moderate opposition's capacity to provide governance and basic services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","19563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437203","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-15","<p>Official food security and nutrition data for Eritrea for this year has not yet been released, but the late onset of rains, relatively low volume of rainfall, and significant soil moisture deficits are likely to have had a negative impact on both farming and pastoral communities. The country and regional offices of the World Food Programme and UNICEF are monitoring the situation closely.</p><br /><p>DFID is funding nutrition support activities in areas affected by El Nino in the Horn of Africa through UNICEF’s regional programme, which covers Eritrea</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437203/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T16:42:09.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437203/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437203/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Eritrea: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of (a) the effect of the drought in the Horn of Africa on Eritrea and (b) the response of the Eritrean government and the international community to that drought.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","19567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437204","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-15","<p>No decisions have yet been made on which prisons will be closed. After the announcement of a closure, the Ministry of Justice will work actively with stakeholders to ensure that we manage the local impact of a prison closure.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437204/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-15T17:42:42.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437204/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437204/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-10","Prisons: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which prisons he intends to close; and what consultation is taking place or is planned to take place on those closures.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","19570"
